		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>lidnariq</b> [ Sat Jan 25, 2014 1:29 pm ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: av mod famicom problems...only black and white</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />For the Famicom, the color information should look like a bunch of marching diagonal lines if the TV is refusing to decode it as color. (If you don't see any, are they visible if you instead plug into the TV component luma/green jack / wire it into the S-video luma pin?)<br /><br />What other pre-gamecube consoles do you have? An Atari 2600 or Sega Master System (or Apple 2, or IBM CGA) have another non-compliant video output: 228 instead of 227.5 master clock cycles. If any of them work, it's unlikely to be the NES's too-short scanline that's to blame.<br /><br />If your TV has s-video input, what happens if you use a simple composite - to - s-video &quot;converter&quot;? By which I mean, connect composite out to Svideo Luma In, and connect that signal via a 690pF capacitor to Svideo Chroma In?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


